data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(x)` to resolve to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls**, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force binding to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the compiler selects the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees.
